{{Orphan|date=December 2014}} [[File:TPPL Day of Dead float, 2009.jpg|thumbnail|Pima County Public Library Day of the Dead float for 2009 procession]] '''All Souls Weekend''' is an event in [[Tucson]], [[Arizona]]. It draws on [[Mesoamerican]], [[Spaniards|Spanish]] [[Roman Catholic]], and [[Mexicans|Mexican]] rituals, incorporating many diverse cultural traditions with the common goal of honoring and remembering the deceased.<ref name="AZ Republic">{{cite web|author1=C. Miller|title=Day of the Dead history: Ritual dating back 3000 years|url=http://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/holidays/day-of-the-dead/2014/09/24/day-of-the-dead-history/16174911/|publisher=The Arizona Republic|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=Palfrey>{{cite web|author1=Dale Hoyt Palfrey|title=Religion and Society in New Spain: Mexico’s Colonial Era|url=http://www.mexconnect.com/articles/1562-religion-and-society-in-new-spain-mexico-s-colonial-era|publisher=MexConnect|accessdate=26 December 2014|date=November 1, 1998}}</ref> <ref name=Carmichael,Sayer>{{cite web|author1=Elizabeth Carmichael,Chloë Sayer|title=The Skeleton at the Feast, the Day of the Dead in Mexico|url=http://www.utexaspress.com/index.php/books/carskp}}</ref>
==Background== All Souls Weekend is more commonly known as All Souls Procession weekend and is derived from the All Souls Procession,[http://www.kgun9.com/news/news-photo-gallery/guy-atchleys-arizona/2015-all-souls-procession-a-celebration-and-mourning-of-loved-ones-in-southern-arizona] an event first initiated and organized in 1990 by Tucson artist Susan Kay Johnson to "express her sorrow" over the recent death of her father and to initiate an artistic ritual in honor of the dead in Tucson.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tucsonweekly.com/tucson/to-mourn-and-to-honor/Content?oid=1519884|title=To Mourn and to Honor|last=Regan|first=Margaret|website=Tucson Weekly|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> Johnson had studied [[art therapy]] based in part on the work of Swiss psychoanalyst [[Carl Jung]]<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_21785043/all-souls-day-tradition-tucson|title=All Souls Day a tradition in Tucson|website=www.mercurynews.com|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> including his study of [[Ritual|rituals]] in cultures around the world.<ref name=":0" /> After her father died, Johnson planned and invited other artists to participate in a three-day ritual, which lasted from [[Halloween]] through [[All Saints' Day|All Saints Day]] and ended on [[All Souls' Day|All Souls Day]]. The ritual took place in public and private spaces in downtown Tucson, and involved art objects Johnson created for the event. These objects included "a giant fabric-and-wire cocoon big enough to hold 15 masked performers who snaked through the neighborhood and emerged as butterflies to dance to the cue of a flute player."<ref name=":1" /> By 1991, public interest the ritual led Johnson and other artists to apply for a grant from the Tucson Partnership in order to involve the Tucson community in the event, through free public workshops in art and music followed by a large [[procession]].[http://manymouths.org/2011/09/a-bit-of-history/] One of the artists listed on the grant application, Mykl Wells, has reported that he helped Johnson write the 1991 grant application, on which his name is spelled "Michael Wells." <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://manymouths.org/2011/09/a-bit-of-history/|title=Many Mouths One Stomach » A Bit of History|website=manymouths.org|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> Wells has reported that he helped inspire Johnson's initial planning of the 1990 All Souls Procession when he told Johnson about ''[[Day of the Dead|Día de los Muertos]]'' rituals he had witnessed in [[Guanajuato]], Mexico in the 1980s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tucsonweekly.com/tucson/all-souls-all-community/Content?oid=4862314|title=All Souls All Community|website=Tucson Weekly|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wildcat.arizona.edu/article/2014/09/artists-show-off-cardboard-crafting-skills-at-charity-event-to-benefit-all-souls-procession|title=Artists show off cardboard crafting skills at charity event to benefit All Souls Procession|website=www.wildcat.arizona.edu|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> ==Controversy== Organizers of All Souls Weekend have made explicit efforts to present the All Souls Procession and associated events as inclusive of but distinct in origin from ''[[Day of the Dead|Día de los Muertos]]'', partly in response to charges of [[cultural appropriation]] by academic critics who have charged that its organizers and participants have primarily been [[Anglo-Americans]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://harlotofthearts.org/issues/issue_14/bentley/memories.html|title=Under the Mask: Creative Dis/Possessions of Borderlands Remembrance Practices {{!}} Lizzy Bentley, Joanna Sanchez-Avila {{!}} Harlot: A Revealing Look at the Arts of Persuasion|website=harlotofthearts.org|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> Similar charges have been directed at the Day of the Dead parade in the [[Mission District, San Francisco|Mission District]] in San Francisco. However, with All Souls Weekend events now bringing together over 100,000 people of varying backgrounds in a public celebration in downtown [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], the organizers influence but do not control the traditions participants choose to represent and honor in the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-ff-all-souls-tucson-20151111-story.html|title=100,000 in Tucson embrace Mexican approach to death with All Souls Procession|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> Each year thousands of participants in All Souls Weekend activities choose to wear [[calavera]]-style makeup and objects, familiar to many in Tucson due to the city's location 50 miles from the US-Mexico border. After the [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|Spanish conquest]] of middle America, ancient Mesoamerican rituals merged with Roman Catholic tradition<ref name="Palfrey" /> along with modern cultural interests in the Americas, yielding the holiday known today as ''[[Day of the Dead|Día de los Muertos]]'' in Spanish or [[Day of the Dead]] in English.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZgIdQeVcS8C|title=Day of the Dead in the USA: The Migration and Transformation of a Cultural Phenomenon|last=Marchi|first=Regina|date=2009-06-09|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=9780813548579|language=en}}</ref> At least one writer has argued that All Soul’s Weekend in Tucson represents a further step in the evolution of [[precolonial]] Mesoamerican rituals and Day of the Dead.<ref name="AZ Republic" /> Though there is evidence the All Souls Procession was directly inspired by the history of [[All Souls' Day|Day of the Dead,]] the organizers of the All Soul’s Weekend emphasize that the event includes and encourages all forms of individual expression, drawing from many cultures, religions, and rituals.<ref name="The All Souls Procession, History">Many Mouths One Stomach. [http://allsoulsprocession.org/history "The All Souls Procession, History"], 2014.</ref> The mission of the weekend’s primary organizing body, [http://manymouths.org/ Many Mouths One Stomach (MMOS)], includes the perspective that death is a universal experience, uniting deceased loved ones with the living. MMOS intends All Soul’s Weekend to serve as an opportunity to approach death in a safe social setting.<ref>Many Mouths One Stomach. [http://manymouths.org/mission/ "Mission"], 2014.</ref> [[File:All Souls Procession 4.jpg|alt=puppets by Sarah Cotten|thumb|A puppet, by artist Sarah Cotten representing her grandmother and mother, in the All Souls Procession.]] ==All Soul's Procession== All Soul’s Weekend culminates with its largest event, a parade called the All Soul’s Procession. According to MMOS, “The All Souls Procession is perhaps one of the most important, inclusive and authentic public ceremonies in [[North America]] today.”<ref name="The All Souls Procession, History"/> Participants often dress up, wear masks, paint their faces, create intricate [[Installation art|artistic installations]], and tow altars, also engaging in numerous other forms of expression in remembrance of the deceased. The deceased may include family, friends, pets, endangered species, fallen heroes, victims of war, or any other group that an individual feels deserving of remembrance. The procession is a forum for the community to engage in open authentic expression of [[grief]], loss, joy, and celebration.<ref name="allsoulsprocession.org">Many Mouths One Stomach. [http://allsoulsprocession.org/faq "The All Souls Procession Weekend, FAQs"], 2014.</ref> The procession is led by a large steel container called The Urn in which procession attendees are invited to place prayers, photographs, and other remembrances of lost loved ones. At the end of the procession, The Urn is set on fire. Burning of The Urn serves the purpose of uniting individual remembrances into a one [[Catharsis|cathartic]] communal expression of both grief and celebration honoring lost loved ones.<ref>Many Mouths One Stomach. [http://manymouths.org/projects/ "Projects: The All Souls Procession Weekend"], 2014.</ref> ==Attendance and Sponsorship== Attendance to, and participation in, All Soul’s Weekend is free to the public. The event itself includes no [[Sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]] advertising. MMOS is a [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organization]] funded exclusively by donations. All Soul’s Weekend costs approximately one dollar per attendee. The total cost for the 2014 procession was $109,850.<ref name="Funding All Soul's Procession">Many Mouths One Stomach., & Infogram. [https://infogr.am/funding-all-souls-procession?src=web "Funding All Soul's Procession] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210035623/https://infogr.am/funding-all-souls-procession?src=web |date=2014-12-10 }}, 2014.</ref> MMOS expresses pride in the community based nature of All Soul’s Weekend and does not intend to seek corporate sponsorship as, “that funding is likely to come with requirements and obligations we are reluctant to take on”.<ref name="allsoulsprocession.org"/> Of all participants in the Procession, an average of 3,000 donate while 97,000 do not. Tax deductible donations from individuals and groups, including businesses and private organizations, may be made to MMOS in support of All Soul’s Weekend.<ref name="Funding All Soul's Procession"/>
